{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621789"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16772"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16772"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.27,0.06,0.56,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9463"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52340"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5043"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22363"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EClass III antiarrhythmic medications are commonly used to treat cardiac arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes their primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreases action potential duration","Increases potassium efflux","Shortens refractory period","Prolongs action potential duration","Blocks sodium channels"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EClass III antiarrhythmic drugs primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolonging the action potential duration\u003C/strong\u003E. By blocking potassium channels, these drugs prevent potassium efflux during repolarisation, which extends the cardiac action potential and increases the effective refractory period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreasing action potential duration\u003C/strong\u003E would promote rather than prevent arrhythmias. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of Class I antiarrhythmic drugs, not Class III drugs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing potassium efflux\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these drugs block rather than increase potassium movement. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShortening the refractory period\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the refractory period is actually prolonged due to the extended action potential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of potassium channel blockers include amiodarone and sotalol. The prolonged refractory period makes the heart less susceptible to premature beats that could trigger arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Class III antiarrhythmic drugs work by blocking potassium channels, which prolongs the cardiac action potential duration.","Prolonging the action potential duration increases the effective refractory period of cardiac tissue.","Potassium channel blockers are used to treat both atrial and ventricular arrhythmias."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52340"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52340"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T07:39:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T07:39:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66886"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite